I.
Thomas Aquinas once said, &ldquo;beware of the man of one book&rdquo;; Scott Alexander once said, &ldquo;beware of the man of one study&rdquo;; I would like to follow in this tradition with my own aphorism, &ldquo;beware of the man of many aphorisms.&rdquo;
This aphorism is the following: in discussions, when someone makes repeated appeals to aphorisms — e.g., &ldquo;don&rsquo;t fix what&rsquo;s not broken,&rdquo; &ldquo;easy come, easy go&rdquo; — then they likely have no idea what they&rsquo;re talking about.
